r: During the first week of Easter, the Pascha Nostrum, without antiphons, is used in place of the Invitatory Psalm, and it may be used throughout Eastertide.
st: pascha nostrum
st:lc: _Christ our Passover_
l:b:Alleluia. Christ our Passover has been sacrificed for us; *
l:b:i: therefore let us keep the feast,
l:b:Not with the old leaven, the leaven of malice and evil, *
l:b:i: but with the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth. Alleluia.
l:b:Christ being raised from the dead will never die again; *
l:b:i: death no longer has dominion over him.
l:b:The death that he died, he died to sin, once for all; *
l:b:i: but the life he lives, he lives to God.
l:b:So also consider yourselves dead to sin, *
l:b:i: and alive to God in Jesus Christ our Lord. Alleluia.
l:b:Christ has been raised from the dead, *
l:b:i: the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep.
l:b:For since by a man came death, *
l:b:i: by a man has come also the resurrection of the dead.
l:b:For as in Adam all die, *
l:b:i: so also in Christ shall all be made alive. Alleluia.
ref: 1 corinthians 5:7-8; romans 6:9-11; 1 corinthians 15:20-22
